 Feldman examines connections between avant-garde literary works; Orientalist historical, geographic and linguistic texts; and political essays written by Russian and Azeri Turkic Muslim writers and thinkers.Tracing these engagements and interactions between Russia and the Caucasus, Feldman offers an alternative vision of empire, modernity, and anti-imperialism from the vantage point not of the metropole but from the cosmopolitan centers at the edges of the Russian and later Soviet empires. In this way, On the Threshold of Eurasia illustrates the pivotal impact that the Caucasus (and the Soviet periphery more broadly) had—through the founding of an avant-garde poetics animated by Russian and Arabo-Persian precursors, Islamic metaphysics, and Marxist-Leninist theories of language —on the monumental aesthetic and political shifts of the early twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAzerbaijani literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCaucasian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aInsurgency in literature. 0aPoeticsxHistoryy20th century. 0aRussian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aHistory. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aEurasianism, global avant-garde, Turkic Poetry, Caucasus, influence of Soviet anti-imperial revolution on literature, Muslim communist consciousness, contemporary geopolitics, Azeri revolutionary poets, Soviet Orientalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is